docs.lead_paragraph: Each Saturday, Farhad Manjoo and Mike Isaac, technology reporters at The New York Times, review the week’s news, offering analysis and maybe a joke or two about the most important developments in the tech industry.

headline.main: Farhad’s and Mike’s Week in Tech: Gaming as Prophylaxis to Elections

byline.original: By Farhad Manjoo and Mike Isaac

docs.abstract: The tech giant introduced Microsoft Teams, an addition to its Office 365 suite, which resembles Slack but adds features like threaded conversations and videoconferencing.
docs.snippet: The tech giant introduced Microsoft Teams, an addition to its Office 365 suite, which resembles Slack but adds features like threaded conversations and videoconferencing.
docs.lead_paragraph: REDMOND, Wash. — In the last couple of years at Microsoft, some old habits have been tossed away, like obsessively placing Windows software at the center of all the company’s big bets. But the company would still dig trenches to protect Office, its $23-billion-a-year software franchise.

headline.main: Microsoft Puts Slack in Cross Hairs With New Office Chat App
headline.print_headline: Microsoft Targets Slack With New Office Chat App

docs.abstract: In charges brought recently against Google and earlier against Microsoft, officials say that each company favored some of its services over those of rivals.
docs.snippet: In charges brought recently against Google and earlier against Microsoft, officials say that each company favored some of its services over those of rivals.
docs.lead_paragraph: Google disputed on Thursday claims made by Europe’s antitrust officials that it had used Android, the company’s dominant mobile operating system, to unfairly promote its own services like online search and its smartphone application store over those of rivals.

headline.main: Parallels Between Europe’s Antitrust Cases Against Google and Microsoft
headline.print_headline: Europe’s Antitrust Cases Against Google and Microsoft

docs.lead_paragraph: PARIS — Carlos Ghosn, chairman and chief executive of the Renault-Nissan car alliance, gives a clear reason his company is taking the lead in developing moderately priced electric cars.

docs.abstract: The computer giant says it’s ready to start planning a prototype quantum computer, a superpowerful device that relies on subatomic particles instead of transistors.

docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Microsoft is putting its considerable financial and engineering muscle into the experimental field of quantum computing as it works to build a machine that could tackle problems beyond the reach of today’s digital computers.

docs.abstract: Fear that Oracle would back away led NetSuite shareholders to accept a $9.3 billion offer over the objections of a major investor, T. Rowe Price.
docs.snippet: Fear that Oracle would back away led NetSuite shareholders to accept a $9.3 billion offer over the objections of a major investor, T. Rowe Price.
docs.lead_paragraph: Larry Ellison, Oracle’s founder, has stored some hardball merger and acquisition tactics in the cloud. He has won his $9.3 billion battle for NetSuite, even though T. Rowe Price, NetSuite’s biggest independent investor, made a strong case for a higher offer.

headline.main: Larry Ellison’s Hardball Tactics Win NetSuite for Oracle
